terns of discrimination. At the core of the book are two dimensions of violence: horizontal 'inter-personal', and vertical 'state policies'. Investigating these dimensions through decisions made by domestic, regional and international judicial or quasi-judicial bodies, De Vido reconceptualises States' obligations and eventually asks whether international law itself is the ultimate cause of violence against women's health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLaw. 0aWomen (International law). 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aWomen's health servicesxLaw and legislation. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aAutonomy.  aDiscrimination.  aFeminism.  aHealth policies.  aHippocratic paradigm.  aHuman rights.  aReproductive health.  aRight to health.  aStates' obligation.  aViolence against women.1 aDe Vido, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526124982zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526124982zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526124982/original  a978-3-11-128248-0 Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA